math.display.latex:

\begin{array}{ccccccc}
a_{11}x_1 & + & \cdots & + & a_{1n}x_n & = & c_1 \\
\vdots &&&& \vdots && \vdots \\
a_{m1}x_1 & + & \cdots & + & a_{mn}x_n & = & c_m
\end{array}

para.para.body:
let 
               \Mtrx{A}
             denote its unaugmented coefficient matrix. Then the system of linear equations has a solution if and only if its augmentation column is in the column space of 
               \Mtrx{A}
            .

math.display.latex:

\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1n} \\
\vdots & \ddots  & \vdots \\
a_{m1} & \cdots & a_{mn}
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
x_1 \\ \vdots \\ x_n
\end{array}
\right] = 
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
c_1 \\ \vdots \\ c_m
\end{array}
\right]


\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
a_{11} & \cdots & a_{1n} \\
\vdots & \ddots  & \vdots \\
a_{m1} & \cdots & a_{mn}
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
x_1 \\ \vdots \\ x_n
\end{array}
\right] = x_1C_1 + \cdots + x_n C_n

para.para.body:
The right hand side of this equation is a linear combination of the column vectors of 
                  \Mtrx{A}
               . The original system of linear equations may now be interpreted as: find all possible ways of expressing the augmentation column

as a linear combination of the column vectors of 
                  \Mtrx{A}
               . In particular, this means that this system of linear equations has a solution if and only if the augmentation column is in the column space of 
                  \Mtrx{A}
               .
